CLIFF LUNGARETTI: I
joked with you earlier

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:41.290
that I blame my entire career
trajectory on my mustache.

00:05:41.290 --> 00:05:44.840
So I know we've talked about
how you said you weren't allowed

00:05:44.840 --> 00:05:46.690
to go to client meetings
with your mustache.

00:05:46.690 --> 00:05:48.810
And how do you feel
that you've actually

00:05:48.810 --> 00:05:53.420
been able to use the Movember
Foundation and the Movember

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:56.760
movement to actually affect
the fashion statement that you

00:05:56.760 --> 00:05:57.570
were talking about?

00:05:57.570 --> 00:05:58.320
ADAM GARONE: Yeah.

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:00.690
I mean, it's been
interesting over the years

00:06:00.690 --> 00:06:04.370
to watch grooming trends change.

00:06:04.370 --> 00:06:09.350
And I'm positive Movember had
a fair bit to do with that.

00:06:09.350 --> 00:06:12.750
And we arguably have
put the mustache back

00:06:12.750 --> 00:06:14.280
on the face of fashion.

00:06:14.280 --> 00:06:16.200
And it's gone even
further than that now.

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:21.310
And beards are in style
for the most part, as well.

00:06:21.310 --> 00:06:24.606
So it's been interesting
to watch that,

00:06:24.606 --> 00:06:27.190
and there's so many
layers to Movember,

00:06:27.190 --> 00:06:30.470
and I often think
about grooming trends

00:06:30.470 --> 00:06:32.850
and how that relates
to masculinity

00:06:32.850 --> 00:06:37.640
and the shift in masculinity
over the last sort of 15 years.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:42.880
And you post that phase
of being a metrosexual

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:46.600
or whatever that
actually ever meant,

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:48.450
probably 10 years
ago, men started

00:06:48.450 --> 00:06:52.670
to express their masculinity
through facial hair.

00:06:52.670 --> 00:06:55.600
And it's been a very,
very interesting journey.

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:57.690
And it's to the extent
now where we even

00:06:57.690 --> 00:06:59.490
need to bring the
mustache back again.

00:06:59.490 --> 00:07:00.760
CLIFF LUNGARETTI: Well, I
think interesting you mentioned

00:07:00.760 --> 00:07:02.200
beards, and I do
know whenever you

00:07:02.200 --> 00:07:03.824
talk to somebody
about, hey, you should

00:07:03.824 --> 00:07:06.310
grow a mustache this Movember,
everyone's just like, oh

00:07:06.310 --> 00:07:08.720
yeah, I'm going to not
shave, which I know something

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:12.624
that we've had with Movember
and then the No-Shave-member

00:07:12.624 --> 00:07:14.040
and all of the
stuff that happens.

00:07:14.040 --> 00:07:16.670
So if we could just
definitively explain

00:07:16.670 --> 00:07:18.980
why it is the mustache
and not the beard.

00:07:18.980 --> 00:07:19.730
ADAM GARONE: Yeah.

00:07:19.730 --> 00:07:22.465
For us, it's about creating
a conversation that matters.

00:07:23.770 --> 00:07:29.370
And our tagline is "Changing
the face of men's health."

00:07:29.370 --> 00:07:31.760
So it's literally about
changing your appearance,

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:34.260
and whether that's going clean
shaven when you've normally

00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:36.590
got a beard and then
growing a mustache.

00:07:36.590 --> 00:07:41.350
And when you do
that, it generates

00:07:41.350 --> 00:07:42.710
so many conversations.

00:07:42.710 --> 00:07:45.790
It's quite amazing how changing
your appearance like that

00:07:45.790 --> 00:07:50.520
does create interest in people.

00:07:50.520 --> 00:07:53.962
And I always say
to guys that are

00:07:53.962 --> 00:07:55.920
on the edge about doing
Movember the first time

00:07:55.920 --> 00:07:58.670
or have done it a few
times and are contemplating

00:07:58.670 --> 00:08:02.430
having a year off, I always
say that I guarantee you,

00:08:02.430 --> 00:08:05.110
because of Movember and
because of your mustache,

00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:08.810
you'll have one really
significant conversation.

00:08:08.810 --> 00:08:11.650
And I've been doing this
12 years, I think, now.

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:17.092
Every year that I do Movember,
I have at least one conversation

00:08:17.092 --> 00:08:18.300
that makes it all worthwhile.

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:20.008
Forget sort of the
funds that are raised.

00:08:20.008 --> 00:08:21.750
And it's quite amazing.

00:08:21.750 --> 00:08:24.050
We've commissioned some
research around how

00:08:24.050 --> 00:08:26.830
do we get men more engaged
in their health beyond just

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:27.330
Movember.

00:08:28.740 --> 00:08:32.000
And there's so many nuances to
approach men with this view.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.370
If you go directly to
men on their health,

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:37.299
typically we shut down.

00:08:37.299 --> 00:08:42.510
And it's so interesting that
the research we did sort of

00:08:42.510 --> 00:08:44.600
uncovered that the women,
generally speaking,

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:47.320
are very good at having
face to face conversations,

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:50.810
like physically face to face
conversations, where men are

00:08:50.810 --> 00:08:53.380
far more comfortable
having shoulder to shoulder

00:08:53.380 --> 00:08:55.530
conversations,
particularly when there's

00:08:55.530 --> 00:08:57.070
something else going on.

00:08:57.070 --> 00:09:01.780
And for us, it's the act
of growing a mustache

00:09:01.780 --> 00:09:04.070
and doing that shoulder to
shoulder with someone else.

00:09:04.070 --> 00:09:05.460
And that creates
this environment

00:09:05.460 --> 00:09:09.110
that the conversation
starts about how good or bad

00:09:09.110 --> 00:09:12.830
your mustache is and then goes
over into often really quite

00:09:12.830 --> 00:09:17.300
serious issues that
we don't normally

00:09:17.300 --> 00:09:18.876
have a bridge to get to.

00:09:18.876 --> 00:09:20.500
CLIFF LUNGARETTI: Very true.

00:09:20.500 --> 00:09:23.390
So we talked about the causes.

00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:28.720
As you said this year,
you're doing mental health

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:29.570
for the first time.

00:09:29.570 --> 00:09:31.420
So what's brought us there?

00:09:31.420 --> 00:09:32.290
ADAM GARONE: Yeah.

00:09:32.290 --> 00:09:35.560
Movember's always
been holistically

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:37.460
about men's health.

00:09:37.460 --> 00:09:40.510
And people often ask us, why
do you focus on men's health?

00:09:41.960 --> 00:09:46.260
The state of men's health
and in boys and men

00:09:46.260 --> 00:09:50.130
is significantly worse
than girls and women.

00:09:50.130 --> 00:09:55.900
And on average, a man dies five
years younger than a woman,

00:09:55.900 --> 00:09:58.590
and there's no biological
reason for that.

00:09:58.590 --> 00:10:01.400
And over the years, the
average age has been going up

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:03.670
and the gap is closing
between men and women

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:06.220
living the same amount of time.

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:09.790
And no one's really
putting a focus on that.

00:10:09.790 --> 00:10:13.000
And I mean, five years is a
significant amount of time.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:17.640
And we know that
if we can improve

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:19.210
the state of men's
health-- and I'm

00:10:19.210 --> 00:10:21.950
talking physically
and mentally here--

00:10:21.950 --> 00:10:24.670
that will improve
society as a whole.

00:10:24.670 --> 00:10:27.560
Children, women, everyone
will benefit from that.

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:31.055
So that's why we're focused
on men's health holistically.

00:10:33.340 --> 00:10:36.860
Our first cause that we decided
to support was prostate cancer.

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:38.705
And as we dove into
this, people often

00:10:38.705 --> 00:10:40.580
go-- because one of the
other co-founder's is

00:10:40.580 --> 00:10:46.010
my brother-- people often
assume that our dad was

00:10:46.010 --> 00:10:48.100
sick from prostate
cancer and that

00:10:48.100 --> 00:10:49.870
was part of the inspiration.

00:10:49.870 --> 00:10:53.970
And we often joke now that, no,
he had a really sick mustache

00:10:53.970 --> 00:10:56.555
back in the day and that
was more the inspiration.

00:10:56.555 --> 00:11:01.870
But started to dive into and
research the cancers that

00:11:01.870 --> 00:11:04.216
affect men-- and
there's two-- and then

00:11:04.216 --> 00:11:06.090
we were just shocked
that prostate cancer has

00:11:06.090 --> 00:11:08.280
the same social impact
as breast cancer.

00:11:10.105 --> 00:11:11.980
Roughly the same number
of men are diagnosed,

00:11:11.980 --> 00:11:15.845
roughly the same amount of
men pass from prostate cancer

00:11:15.845 --> 00:11:18.050
as women with breast cancer.

00:11:18.050 --> 00:11:19.690
And you only need
to look around now

00:11:19.690 --> 00:11:21.606
during October, Breast
Cancer Awareness Month,

00:11:21.606 --> 00:11:25.660
to see the amazing number of
cause marketing initiatives

00:11:25.660 --> 00:11:26.860
for that cause.

00:11:27.512 --> 00:11:29.470
And if you sort of take
Movember off the table,

00:11:29.470 --> 00:11:31.820
there's really
nothing else out there

00:11:31.820 --> 00:11:33.570
of any sort of scale
or significance

00:11:33.570 --> 00:11:34.790
for prostate cancer.

00:11:34.790 --> 00:11:38.010
So that became
our initial focus.

00:11:39.850 --> 00:11:44.300
And then when we got
some scale, we then

00:11:44.300 --> 00:11:47.050
also started to attack
testicular cancer.

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:50.430
And that's a rare,
highly curable disease,

00:11:50.430 --> 00:11:51.930
but it's the most
common cancer that

00:11:51.930 --> 00:11:54.170
affects young men--
so 17 to sort of 35.

00:11:55.870 --> 00:12:00.830
And as you know, a lot of the
guys participating in Movember

00:12:00.830 --> 00:12:03.280
are in that age range,
versus prostate cancer

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:07.040
is a disease that when
you're in your 40s plus,

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:09.450
you need to be
really conscious of.

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:12.410
And so that was
the initial focus.

00:12:12.410 --> 00:12:15.390
And then mental health.

00:12:15.390 --> 00:12:17.860
And we often get asked,
well, obviously, that

00:12:17.860 --> 00:12:18.820
affects men and women.

00:12:18.820 --> 00:12:23.080
But when you dive
into that issue

00:12:23.080 --> 00:12:26.010
and look at the
statistics, it's really

00:12:26.010 --> 00:12:27.680
quite a sad story for men.

00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:30.560
So three out of four
suicides are men.

00:12:33.440 --> 00:12:36.260
Men often don't understand
the signs and symptoms

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:38.110
of a mental illness.

00:12:38.110 --> 00:12:40.622
Men are typically
good at masking those,

00:12:40.622 --> 00:12:42.830
whether it's diving into
work, whether it's drinking,

00:12:42.830 --> 00:12:46.250
or whatever it is, and
not good at seeking help.

00:12:46.250 --> 00:12:52.835
And in the US, it's about 83
men a day take their lives.

00:12:54.140 --> 00:12:59.070
And so often, imagine
if 83 guys washed

00:12:59.070 --> 00:13:02.680
on the shores of, say, Santa
Monica Beach tomorrow morning.

00:13:02.680 --> 00:13:04.596
That would be global
and national news.

00:13:04.596 --> 00:13:05.970
And then it happened
the next day

00:13:05.970 --> 00:13:07.450
and the next day
and the next day.

00:13:07.450 --> 00:13:13.850
And it's just an issue that
is not being spoken about,

00:13:13.850 --> 00:13:17.280
and we're putting
the a large torch

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:21.210
to this in terms of the issue
from a mile perspective.

00:13:21.210 --> 00:13:24.540
So it's really four causes--
men's health holistically,

00:13:24.540 --> 00:13:27.060
prostate and testicular
cancer, and then mental health.

