have an avalanche
of traffic that

00:24:18.580 --> 00:24:23.440
starts to ramp up now and
then throughout November.

00:24:23.440 --> 00:24:25.780
So one of our
challenges is we only

00:24:25.780 --> 00:24:29.140
get to do this once a year,
so the tuning we're doing

00:24:29.140 --> 00:24:31.920
and the testing and the
experiments the guys

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:36.360
are doing on different
buttons and different paths,

00:24:36.360 --> 00:24:38.360
we do a lot of that
in October, and then

00:24:38.360 --> 00:24:41.790
we sort of lock it down because
we can't afford for their to be

00:24:41.790 --> 00:24:43.360
any issues with the platform.

00:24:43.360 --> 00:24:49.280
But it is interesting that
even though we are a charity,

00:24:49.280 --> 00:24:52.155
people expect the
technology experience, be it

00:24:52.155 --> 00:24:58.395
on mobile or on a computer, to
be as good as they experience

00:24:58.395 --> 00:25:01.680
at Google or
Facebook or Instagram

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:04.660
or whatever it is
they're used to using.

00:25:04.660 --> 00:25:07.670
When they come across to us and
it's not as seamless to sign up

00:25:07.670 --> 00:25:10.210
or whatever it is,
they're out the door.

00:25:10.210 --> 00:25:14.510
And so we spend a lot of
time thinking about the user

00:25:14.510 --> 00:25:16.910
interface and the
paths people go down

00:25:16.910 --> 00:25:19.740
to make it as simple and
as intuitive as possible.

00:25:21.580 --> 00:25:22.830
CLIFF LUNGARETTI: Interesting.

00:25:22.830 --> 00:25:27.980
And how does the technology in
the Movember programs kind of

00:25:27.980 --> 00:25:28.810
come together?

00:25:28.810 --> 00:25:32.130
ADAM GARONE: Yeah, there's a
couple of areas that we do.

00:25:32.130 --> 00:25:37.510
So the collaboration piece that
I talked about, one of the ways

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:39.110
we get the researchers
collaborating

00:25:39.110 --> 00:25:43.470
is through a sort of
Wiki-based platform.

00:25:43.470 --> 00:25:46.130
So again, it was
an off the shelf

00:25:46.130 --> 00:25:47.630
product that we've packaged up.

00:25:47.630 --> 00:25:52.190
And yeah, they are able to
come together online and share

00:25:52.190 --> 00:25:52.690
things.

00:25:52.690 --> 00:25:55.210
And it's quite
amazing that you see

00:25:55.210 --> 00:25:56.830
these conversations happening.

00:25:56.830 --> 00:25:58.975
There will be a
researcher saying--

00:25:58.975 --> 00:26:01.150
I think it was the
Netherlands posed

00:26:01.150 --> 00:26:03.610
a question in a
particular forum,

00:26:03.610 --> 00:26:06.060
and then there was a guy,
I think, from New York--

00:26:06.060 --> 00:26:07.870
a researcher-- that
said, hey, yeah, we've

00:26:07.870 --> 00:26:09.520
been down this path.

00:26:09.520 --> 00:26:11.360
Here are all the results.

00:26:11.360 --> 00:26:12.255
It ended in this.

00:26:13.476 --> 00:26:15.100
I wouldn't suggest
going down that path

00:26:15.100 --> 00:26:17.350
because it didn't lead anywhere.

00:26:17.350 --> 00:26:20.130
So for that, the researchers
in the Netherlands

00:26:20.130 --> 00:26:21.550
then iterate off
of that, and then

00:26:21.550 --> 00:26:23.008
that whole community
that's focused

00:26:23.008 --> 00:26:26.970
on that particular project,
to able to observe that

00:26:26.970 --> 00:26:29.660
is really, really powerful.

00:26:29.660 --> 00:26:34.037
The other thing that
we're doing-- as I say,

00:26:34.037 --> 00:26:35.870
we'll get to a stage
where we'll effectively

00:26:35.870 --> 00:26:38.080
cure these diseases,
but it doesn't

00:26:38.080 --> 00:26:40.350
mean we've got a vaccine
coming anytime soon that'll

00:26:40.350 --> 00:26:42.735
wipe them off the table.

00:26:43.910 --> 00:26:47.380
So as we live older,
there's going to be more men

00:26:47.380 --> 00:26:50.670
and their families going through
the prostate or testicular

00:26:50.670 --> 00:26:53.410
cancer journey--
particularly prostate.

00:26:53.410 --> 00:26:56.370
And so we're
developing new program.

00:26:56.370 --> 00:26:58.165
It's called True North.

00:26:58.165 --> 00:26:59.540
It's our biggest
investment ever.

00:26:59.540 --> 00:27:01.390
It's like $40 million globally.

00:27:02.830 --> 00:27:07.540
That's going to provide a
whole range of applications

00:27:07.540 --> 00:27:11.900
and products to allow
the guy and his family

00:27:11.900 --> 00:27:15.390
to navigate through
this whole journey.

00:27:15.390 --> 00:27:18.350
And the journey being from
the time of diagnosis,

00:27:18.350 --> 00:27:20.480
through treatment, and
then life after treatment.

00:27:20.480 --> 00:27:25.910
So it'll help them
access clinical trials.

00:27:25.910 --> 00:27:29.210
It'll advise them on
optimal diet and exercise.

00:27:29.210 --> 00:27:30.960
It'll connect them
with other people going

00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:34.910
through the same journey if they
want to chat with other men,

00:27:34.910 --> 00:27:38.390
or the caregivers
can do that as well.

00:27:38.390 --> 00:27:42.630
It'll sure, if you're
in New York, what

00:27:42.630 --> 00:27:45.810
facilities and things
that are around you,

00:27:45.810 --> 00:27:48.930
and similarly with wherever
you are in the country.

00:27:50.790 --> 00:27:55.120
Because one of the big
issues is the access often

00:27:55.120 --> 00:27:57.130
that you have to
medical services

00:27:57.130 --> 00:27:59.620
is defined by where you live.

00:27:59.620 --> 00:28:01.360
And if you live in
New York, there's

00:28:01.360 --> 00:28:04.460
an amazing array of
institutions, organizations,

00:28:04.460 --> 00:28:05.580
and research going on.

00:28:05.580 --> 00:28:09.340
But if you're
Alabama or somewhere,

00:28:09.340 --> 00:28:12.550
there's just not, and so being
able to through technology

00:28:12.550 --> 00:28:13.355
connect everyone.

00:28:15.060 --> 00:28:18.330
And there's a quarter
of a million guys

00:28:18.330 --> 00:28:21.740
a year get diagnosed just in
the US with prostate cancer.

00:28:21.740 --> 00:28:24.435
So we're just starting
down that path now,

00:28:24.435 --> 00:28:28.830
and we've connected about 10
institutions across the US

00:28:28.830 --> 00:28:30.719
to work on this
technology platform.

00:28:30.719 --> 00:28:32.010
CLIFF LUNGARETTI: That's great.

00:28:33.384 --> 00:28:35.800
Is there anybody here in the
house that has any questions?

00:28:35.800 --> 00:28:37.810
We have two microphones
in the aisle ways.

00:28:37.810 --> 00:28:40.515
If anyone wants to step up,
I'll just throw it over to you.

00:28:40.515 --> 00:28:41.390
But just let me know.

00:28:41.390 --> 00:28:43.515
I think we've got some
lights coming on over those.

00:28:43.515 --> 00:28:44.259
Yes?

00:28:44.259 --> 00:28:46.300
AUDIENCE: Any particular
mustache style you think

00:28:46.300 --> 00:28:49.300
should be stopped and
not allowed to occur?

00:28:50.670 --> 00:28:53.194
ADAM GARONE: Well, there's
the obvious one, isn't there?

00:28:53.194 --> 00:28:54.110
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:54.880 --> 00:28:57.920
ADAM GARONE: Yeah, the-- well,
we call it a Charlie Chaplin.

00:28:57.920 --> 00:28:58.400
CLIFF LUNGARETTI:
It's the Chaplin.

00:28:58.400 --> 00:28:58.900
Yeah.

00:28:58.900 --> 00:29:00.970
ADAM GARONE: Yeah,
it's the Chaplin, which

00:29:00.970 --> 00:29:03.300
he did a lot of bad
shit, and one of them

00:29:03.300 --> 00:29:06.110
was banishing that style.

00:29:07.156 --> 00:29:08.530
So yeah, that
would be the go-to.

00:29:10.440 --> 00:29:14.340
AUDIENCE: The more real
question is you clearly

00:29:14.340 --> 00:29:16.590
didn't set out your
life to do this.

00:29:16.590 --> 00:29:18.650
It's become a passion of yours.

00:29:18.650 --> 00:29:21.199
What keeps you involved
year after year?

00:29:21.199 --> 00:29:22.990
ADAM GARONE: Yeah, it's
funny you say that.

00:29:22.990 --> 00:29:24.880
It's like every day
I wake up and go,

00:29:24.880 --> 00:29:26.895
somehow my life has
become about a mustache.

00:29:27.940 --> 00:29:30.265
And when you stop, step
back, and think about it,

00:29:30.265 --> 00:29:33.530
it's ridiculous
that this happened.

00:29:34.850 --> 00:29:37.160
But it's far more than that now.

00:29:37.160 --> 00:29:41.280
And I often talk about a
lot and think about a lot

00:29:41.280 --> 00:29:43.640
the difference between
being successful and being

00:29:43.640 --> 00:29:44.140
significant.

00:29:45.350 --> 00:29:49.590
I think on reflection, we
spend a lot of-- the first half

00:29:49.590 --> 00:29:52.380
of our life trying
to be successful,

00:29:52.380 --> 00:29:55.790
and whether that's academics,
with sports, with work, getting

00:29:55.790 --> 00:29:58.180
more promotions and
all that sort of stuff.

00:29:58.180 --> 00:30:00.270
I think-- and certainly
for me on reflection--

00:30:00.270 --> 00:30:02.250
there was a point
in my life where

00:30:02.250 --> 00:30:04.740
that was great, but wanted
to do something significant.

00:30:04.740 --> 00:30:07.620
And for me, doing
something significant

00:30:07.620 --> 00:30:11.460
is serving other
people or a cause

00:30:11.460 --> 00:30:14.220
that you can truly
have an impact on.

00:30:14.220 --> 00:30:16.710
And when you get into
this space and you

00:30:16.710 --> 00:30:19.210
meet so many great people and
you hear so many great stories

00:30:19.210 --> 00:30:24.140
about how a dodgy-looking
mustache actually transformed

00:30:24.140 --> 00:30:27.830
and changed someone's
life-- beyond the research

00:30:27.830 --> 00:30:31.110
we're funding-- and
becomes quite addictive.

00:30:31.110 --> 00:30:35.140
And what motivates
me now is we've

00:30:35.140 --> 00:30:38.990
done a great job of building
all this financial capital,

00:30:38.990 --> 00:30:42.230
and now what's coming
along is this human capital

00:30:42.230 --> 00:30:44.680
and the researchers and
connecting them, and just

00:30:44.680 --> 00:30:49.350
seeing that interaction and
the progress they're making

00:30:49.350 --> 00:30:50.200
is quite amazing.

00:30:50.200 --> 00:30:53.640
And there's no other
cancer category

00:30:53.640 --> 00:30:55.460
that's able to do this.

00:30:55.460 --> 00:30:58.840
If you look at other
cancer categories, at best,

00:30:58.840 --> 00:31:02.160
organizations like ours
that are nationally focused,

00:31:02.160 --> 00:31:06.620
there's no international
organization like ours

00:31:06.620 --> 00:31:09.040
that has that reach and ability
to bring people together.

00:31:09.040 --> 00:31:14.710
So for me, it's that impact
and seeing this progress now

00:31:14.710 --> 00:31:15.780
on the research side.

00:31:16.920 --> 00:31:18.737
That's what gets
me up every day.

00:31:20.120 --> 00:31:21.784
As well as this, of course.

00:31:24.295 --> 00:31:25.420
CLIFF LUNGARETTI: Yes, sir?

00:31:25.420 --> 00:31:26.590
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:31:26.590 --> 00:31:28.950
So I'm actually
in college still.

00:31:28.950 --> 00:31:29.840
I'm an intern here.

00:31:29.840 --> 00:31:32.950
And I know a lot of college
students take part in Movember,

00:31:32.950 --> 00:31:35.167
but a lot of them don't
know what it's about,

00:31:35.167 --> 00:31:39.550
and even more don't get
involved in fundraising at all.

00:31:39.550 --> 00:31:42.897
So I was wondering if you
have any strategies to sort

00:31:42.897 --> 00:31:44.730
of leverage that untapped
potential in terms

00:31:44.730 --> 00:31:46.605
of fundraising and just
spreading information

00:31:46.605 --> 00:31:47.522
about what it's about?

00:31:47.522 --> 00:31:48.271
ADAM GARONE: Yeah.

00:31:48.271 --> 00:31:49.070
I mean, we do.

00:31:49.070 --> 00:31:50.955
Yeah, there's a lot
of guys that-- I mean,

00:31:50.955 --> 00:31:53.080
if you're doing Movember
and you're not registered,

00:31:53.080 --> 00:31:56.430
then you're just
a creep, really.

00:31:56.430 --> 00:31:57.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:57.720 --> 00:32:01.160
ADAM GARONE: So we try
and shame people into it.

00:32:02.570 --> 00:32:03.070
But we do.

00:32:03.070 --> 00:32:06.870
We have-- and [? JJ's ?] up in
the back of the room there--

00:32:06.870 --> 00:32:10.050
a group of people focused
on college engagement.

00:32:10.050 --> 00:32:15.100
And it's a market that's turning
over all the time as people

00:32:15.100 --> 00:32:17.120
come into and then
leave, and hopefully

00:32:17.120 --> 00:32:20.620
type the Movember journey
into their workplace.

00:32:22.510 --> 00:32:24.640
So yeah, we've got
active programs

00:32:24.640 --> 00:32:28.980
to tap into the college
market through the athletics

00:32:28.980 --> 00:32:31.320
apartment, through
the fraternities,

00:32:31.320 --> 00:32:36.810
and then champions on campus
to help us spread that message.

00:32:36.810 --> 00:32:37.850
Because it is important.

00:32:37.850 --> 00:32:42.940
Like the fundraising
part aside, it's

00:32:42.940 --> 00:32:45.290
great that people
raise money, but we

00:32:45.290 --> 00:32:47.370
don't push that hard on that.

00:32:47.370 --> 00:32:51.080
For us, what's really
important is signing up,

00:32:51.080 --> 00:32:52.750
because when you
do that, you get

00:32:52.750 --> 00:32:56.300
then armed with why it's
important you do it.

00:32:56.300 --> 00:33:00.870
And we use growing
mustaches as a Trojan horse

00:33:00.870 --> 00:33:03.440
for getting men
involved in this thing.

00:33:03.440 --> 00:33:05.910
And that's the most
important thing for us,

00:33:05.910 --> 00:33:08.617
that they are
knowledgeable-- or more

00:33:08.617 --> 00:33:10.200
knowledgeable than
at start-- and that

00:33:10.200 --> 00:33:13.832
will enable them to have that
conversation that matters.

00:33:13.832 --> 00:33:15.040
But there's no easy strategy.

00:33:17.280 --> 00:33:18.260
It's hard.

00:33:18.260 --> 00:33:21.780
But as Movember
becomes more known,

00:33:21.780 --> 00:33:24.390
people do realize that
it's important to sign up.

00:33:24.390 --> 00:33:27.510
We actually have got a
video-- we'll send it to you--

00:33:27.510 --> 00:33:29.870
with Samuel L Jackson
doing the voiceover--

00:33:29.870 --> 00:33:30.290
CLIFF LUNGARETTI: [INAUDIBLE].

00:33:30.290 --> 00:33:31.040
ADAM GARONE: Yeah.

00:33:31.040 --> 00:33:33.360
It's like-- what's the
title of that video?

00:33:33.360 --> 00:33:34.720
Do you remember?

00:33:34.720 --> 00:33:35.440
It's basically--

00:33:35.440 --> 00:33:37.560
CLIFF LUNGARETTI: It's very-- as
you said, it's shaming people.

00:33:37.560 --> 00:33:39.185
ADAM GARONE: Yeah,
it's shaming people.

00:33:39.185 --> 00:33:41.342
If you don't register,
you're a loser, essentially.

00:33:41.342 --> 00:33:42.243
AUDIENCE: Good.

00:33:42.243 --> 00:33:43.326
ADAM GARONE: Thanks, mate.

00:33:44.820 --> 00:33:46.049
CLIFF LUNGARETTI: Yes, sir?

00:33:46.049 --> 00:33:48.340
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so most of
the marketing and everything

00:33:48.340 --> 00:33:52.050
is aimed at men, but more
women-- who may not be able to

00:33:52.050 --> 00:33:55.580
also grow a mustache-- how
can they be involved as well?

00:33:55.580 --> 00:33:58.450
ADAM GARONE: Yeah, So we've got
a Mo Sista program, and the Mo

00:33:58.450 --> 00:34:01.360
Sista program, it's so
critically important for us.

00:34:02.900 --> 00:34:06.640
As I mentioned, the Mo Sistas
are often the gatekeeper for us

00:34:06.640 --> 00:34:07.689
to participate.

00:34:09.370 --> 00:34:14.139
And we encourage that Mo Sistas
sign up as a team captain,

00:34:14.139 --> 00:34:16.980
recruit the guys in their
life to be part of their team,

00:34:16.980 --> 00:34:18.880
and then encourage them to grow.

00:34:20.469 --> 00:34:22.280
A program that I'm
working on, which

00:34:22.280 --> 00:34:27.250
we'll look to launch next year,
it's a program called Move.

00:34:27.250 --> 00:34:29.940
So the first four letters
of Movember are "move."

00:34:29.940 --> 00:34:31.462
And one of the most
important things

00:34:31.462 --> 00:34:33.420
you can do for your health
throughout your life

00:34:33.420 --> 00:34:35.900
is staying active and moving.

00:34:35.900 --> 00:34:37.429
And I don't mean
going to the gym.

00:34:37.429 --> 00:34:38.820
I mean just being active.

00:34:38.820 --> 00:34:40.500
We've built-- this life.

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:43.414
Because of wonderful
technology, we've

00:34:43.414 --> 00:34:44.705
built this sedentary lifestyle.

00:34:45.477 --> 00:34:47.310
And there's all this
research coming out now

00:34:47.310 --> 00:34:50.800
around the impact of seating
for six to eight hours a day,

00:34:50.800 --> 00:34:54.460
and it is as bad if
not worse than smoking.

00:34:54.460 --> 00:34:58.115
So if you're sitting for six
to eight hours a day and smoke,

00:34:58.115 --> 00:34:59.240
you're in a lot of trouble.

00:35:00.370 --> 00:35:03.899
So for us, Move--
next year, you'll

00:35:03.899 --> 00:35:05.940
be able to sign up and
make a commitment to move.

00:35:05.940 --> 00:35:09.720
And that will enable the
Mo Sistas to do actually

00:35:09.720 --> 00:35:12.490
something tangible, make
a tangible commitment

00:35:12.490 --> 00:35:13.245
during Movember.

00:35:13.245 --> 00:35:15.120
And the way we'll tie
it back to men's health

00:35:15.120 --> 00:35:18.540
is if a Mo Sista does
that, they'll then

00:35:18.540 --> 00:35:21.110
be encouraged to issue
a challenge to the men

00:35:21.110 --> 00:35:23.230
in their life to
match their move.

00:35:23.230 --> 00:35:26.130
And it'll be a great
way-- we'll sort of track

00:35:26.130 --> 00:35:27.640
that activity then online.

00:35:27.640 --> 00:35:31.190
And over time, we'll integrate
the wearable technology

00:35:31.190 --> 00:35:35.260
to make sure that
if they're walking

00:35:35.260 --> 00:35:36.790
a certain amount
of time per day,

00:35:36.790 --> 00:35:38.680
that that's actually happening.

00:35:38.680 --> 00:35:41.236
so we're sort of particularly
excited about the Move program,

00:35:41.236 --> 00:35:43.360
and as I said, that'll come
to life more next year.

00:35:46.102 --> 00:35:48.845
CLIFF LUNGARETTI: All right,
so what is your ideal mustache?

00:35:51.130 --> 00:35:52.600
ADAM GARONE: Ideal mustache.

00:35:52.600 --> 00:35:53.960
This is my go-to stache.

00:35:53.960 --> 00:35:54.650
CLIFF LUNGARETTI:
That's your go-to?

00:35:54.650 --> 00:35:55.400
ADAM GARONE: Yeah.

